keystone_auto_managed_settings:
  description: "Flag ks-config host settings that should be auto-set by keystone modules from keystone.os.agents / keystone.os.users declarations."
  match:
    include:
      - "hosts/**/*.nix"
      - "modules/**/*.nix"
  review:
    strategy: individual
    instructions: |
      Review this NixOS file for settings that ks-config is declaring manually
      when they should instead be auto-declared by a keystone module given the
      higher-level `keystone.os.agents.*` (or related) configuration.

      ## Background

      ks-config consumes the keystone flake input. Many low-level options
      (`age.secrets.*`, systemd services, users.users.*, home-manager modules,
      etc.) are wired up automatically by keystone modules in
      `../keystone/modules/os/` once an agent or user is declared via
      `keystone.os.agents.<name> = { ... }` or `keystone.os.users.<name> = ...`.

      When ks-config redeclares those values, two things go wrong:
      1. The host config carries boilerplate that should not be its concern.
      2. Drift: keystone evolves its naming/owner/mode conventions, but the
         hand-declared copies in ks-config silently diverge.

      ## What to Flag

      Flag any block in this file that looks like it is doing work the
      keystone module should do. Common patterns to look for:

      - `age.secrets.agent-<name>-*` or `age.secrets.<host>-agent-<name>-*`
        entries — per-agent secrets (ssh key, ssh passphrase, mail password,
        tailscale auth key, bitwarden password, etc.) should be declared by
        the relevant keystone agent module
        (`../keystone/modules/os/agents/{ssh,mail-client,tailscale,...}.nix`)
        based on `keystone.os.agents.<name>` and the agent's `host`. The host
        config should only declare the agent identity in `agent-identities.nix`.
      - Manual `users.users.agent-<name>` definitions, group memberships, or
        `home-manager.users.agent-<name>` blocks for declared agents.
      - Per-agent systemd services (ssh-agent, mail-trigger, etc.) when an
        archetype module already provides them.
      - `keystone.terminal.*`, `keystone.notes.*` per-user wiring that the
        archetype/user module would set from `keystone.os.users.<name>`.

      ## How to Check

      1. Open `../keystone/modules/os/agents/` (and sibling modules) and skim
         for `mkIf`-gated blocks that mirror the suspect declaration. If a
         keystone module already sets the same option for any agent whose
         `host == config.networking.hostName`, the ks-config declaration is
         redundant.
      2. Confirm by reading `agent-identities.nix` (or equivalent) — if the
         agent is declared there, the per-agent infrastructure should be
         automatic.
      3. If keystone does NOT currently auto-manage the value but logically
         should, flag it as a keystone gap. The fix belongs in keystone — but
         while a change is mid-flight (not yet merged / pinned in
         `flake.lock`), the staging location is `modules/keystone/`, NOT host
         configs or scattered modules. See `modules/keystone/AGENTS.md`:
         experimental keystone-shaped code lives under `modules/keystone/`
         (e.g. `modules/keystone/os/...`) so it can move into `../keystone`
         unchanged once promoted. Flag any keystone-style logic that has
         leaked outside `modules/keystone/` and recommend relocating it.

      ## What NOT to Flag

      - Genuinely host-specific values (hardware config, disk layout, network
        interfaces, host-unique service config, secrets owned by a non-agent
        principal).
      - Bootstrapping or override cases where the comment / surrounding code
        explicitly documents why the manual declaration is necessary.

      ## Output Format

      - PASS: No host-level declarations duplicate keystone-managed settings.
      - FAIL: For each finding, list the file:line, the redundant block, the
        keystone module that should own it (or note "keystone gap" if none
        exists yet), and the suggested fix (delete from ks-config, or open a
        keystone change first).
